Algorithm 1 <p>The problem can be efficiently solved using a Trie data structure to store all the words. This allows for quick lookups and ensures that we only explore paths that could potentially form words.</p> <p>We perform a Depth-First Search (DFS) starting from each cell in the board. During the DFS, we mark cells as visited by changing their value to <code>#</code>, and restore them after exploring all possible paths from that cell to avoid using the same cell more than once in a single word.</p> <p>After finding a word, we set its corresponding node's <code>word</code> attribute to <code>None</code> to prevent adding it multiple times to the result list. Additionally, we prune the Trie by removing leaf nodes that no longer have children, which helps in reducing unnecessary computations in subsequent searches.</p> Python <pre><code>class TrieNode:
    def __init__(self):
        self.children = {}
        self.word = None  # When a word ends at this node

class Solution:
    def findWords(self, board: List[List[str]], words: List[str]) -&gt; List[str]:
        # Build the Trie
        root = TrieNode()
        for word in words:
            node = root
            for char in word:
                if char not in node.children:
                    node.children[char] = TrieNode()
                node = node.children[char]
            node.word = word  # Mark the end of a word

        R, C = len(board), len(board[0])
        ans = []
        directions = [(-1, 0), (1, 0), (0, -1), (0, 1)]  # Left, Right, Down, Up

        def dfs(i, j, parent):
            # Out of bounds check
            if i &lt; 0 or i &gt;= R or j &lt; 0 or j &gt;= C:
                return

            char = board[i][j]
            # Visited check
            if char == '#':
                return

            #if the character is not in the current Trie node
            if char not in parent.children:
                return

            node = parent.children[char]

            # Check if we found a word
            if node.word:
                ans.append(node.word)
                node.word = None  # Avoid duplicate entries

            # Mark the current cell as visited
            board[i][j] = '#'

            # Explore neighbors
            for di, dj in directions:
                dfs(i + di, j + dj, node)

            # Restore the current cell
            board[i][j] = char

            # Optimization: remove the leaf node to save memory and time
            if not node.children:
                parent.children.pop(char)

        for r in range(R):
            for c in range(C):
                if board[r][c] in root.children:
                    dfs(r, c, root)

        return ans
</code></pre> <p>Detailed Complexity Discussion</p> <p>Time: \(O(m*n*4^L)\) where \(m\) and \(n\) are the dimensions of the board, and \(L\) is the maximum length of the words in the dictionary. In practice, the pruning step significantly reduces the number of recursive calls, making the algorithm much faster for larger inputs.</p> <p>Space: \(O(T)\) where \(T\) is the total number of characters in the dictionary of words. This accounts for the space used by the Trie structure. Additionally, the recursion stack during DFS adds to the space complexity, but it is bounded by the size of the board.</p> <p>Algorithm 2</p> <ul> <li>Extension of LC 79 Word Search</li> <li>TLE</li> </ul>

